Tom,<br>
In regards to my e-mail, I will and HAVE provided to those people on line that I deem necessary.  It is obvious that with your attitude that nothing good came come of giving you my e-mail.  Explain to me why you in particular need my e-mail?  I don't mind providing it to someone else that needs it, but you still have not explained why you need it.  Is it because you doubt my authenticity as a human.  The state of Pennsylvania has my teaching and college credentials on file as well as my license to be a NOTARY PUBLIC on file.  I assure you I am real.  E-mail doen't prove a man's existence, nor does a website.  Don't you know anything about cyberspace?  If you in particular need to say something to me, that can be done here.  I am a credible person, a tax payer, a college graduate (on state files), a state notary public, a student of history, a person trained in the art of school teaching, the son of a Vietnam vet (My father is credible too!)etc.  I am Joseph DeLeva!! My credentials are solid.  I am a real person, and if you doubt me for a moment, that is your problem. <br><br>
As for this discussion, I'm sorry you are so closed minded, I might have met you half way on this issue, and explored in the subject in a scholary fashion.  Instead we all lose.  As for your words archived for prosterity, that they are, but they are the view of one man, as are my words also and everyone elses.  Go on attacking fellow Vietnam vets and I will go on defending these men.  If you don't like my views, I'm sorry, but I will not be silenced, I have the right to them.  I guess I need to rethink my respect for ALL Vietnam vets.  Yes, you have website, I am also building a website on Vietnam, exercising my right to do so. One final thought, if you want to treat as annonymous poster, that is fine with me, since I believe we have nothing else to say to each other in Vietnam discussion.  It is shame that you can ignore and try to silence others who disagree, since that is what America did to the Vietnam vet and now you do it to others.  I really feel sorry for you.  You can't talk to someone who is willing to DISCUSS an issue with someone who was not alive in the 1960's and not a Vet of the Vietnam war.  &quot;There is nothing further to say to you by me.&quot;    
